<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901221-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>901221-0016.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Yerkes andamp; Michels:   Accounting Firm Is Banned   From Serving Any Thrifts</HL><DATE>12/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)ACCOUNTING (ACC)</IN><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   The Office of Thrift Supervision permanently banned Yerkesandamp; Michels, an accounting firm based in Independence, Kan.,from serving any thrift, thrift-holding company or subsidiarythat is federally regulated.   Under a consent order in connection with the firm's auditof First Federal Savings andamp; Loan Association of Independence,the thrift office charged that the 1988 and 1989 auditsweren't conducted by qualified public accountants. The thriftoffice also said that Yerkes andamp; Michels reported the truefinancial condition of First Federal, which meets all capitalrequirements, but that it relied on government examiners'paperwork, and didn't independently review the thrift.</LP><TEXT>   Yerkes andamp; Michels couldn't be reached for comment. Underthe consent order, the firm neither admits nor denies thegrounds of the order.   The thrift office also issued a cease-and-desist orderrequiring Yerkes andamp; Michels to correct its auditing practices,and repay audit fees of $51,000 that the firm charged FirstFederal. It must also establish minimum credentials for anypartners and staff assigned to bank or credit union audits.</TEXT></DOC>